Revolution Consulting Data Modeling Report¶

1. Setting the Research Goal¶

This section establishes the purpose and scope of our analysis, aligning it with Revolution Consulting's business needs.

1.1 Statement of Research Goal¶

How can Revolution Consulting improve consultant retention and attract top talent in order to maintain and enhance the quality of its consulting services?

1.2 Project Mission¶

In the context of Revolution Consulting's challenges with declining work quality and increased employee turnover, our mission is to:

  1. Analyze employee data to uncover patterns related to attrition.
  2. Segment employees into distinct groups based on their characteristics and risk of leaving.
  3. Provide actionable insights and recommendations to improve employee retention and satisfaction.

This analysis will help Revolution Consulting address their concerns about losing valuable consultants and ultimately improve the quality of work delivered to clients.

# Function to visualize the distribution of variables
def create_grid(df, columns, num_rows=None, num_cols=None, bins=20):

  fig, axs = plt.subplots(num_rows, num_cols, figsize=(16, 12))

  for i, col in enumerate(columns):
    row, col_idx = i // num_cols, i % num_cols
    ax = axs[row, col_idx] if num_rows > 1 else axs[col_idx]

    def add_summary(summary_text, x_pos=0.95, y_pos=0.95, va='top', ha='right'):
      ax.text(x_pos, y_pos, summary_text, transform=ax.transAxes, fontsize=8,
               verticalalignment=va, horizontalalignment=ha, bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5))

    if df[col].dtype == 'object':
      # Categorical variables
      value_counts = df[col].value_counts()
      total = value_counts.sum()
      percentages = (value_counts / total * 100).round(1)

      sns.countplot(x=col, data=df, ax=ax)
      ax.set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')

      # Add percentage labels
      for i, v in enumerate(value_counts):
        ax.text(i, v, f'{percentages[i]}%', ha='center', va='bottom')

      # Add summary
      summary = f"Total: {total}\n" + "\n".join([f"{val}: {count} ({pct}%)" for val, count, pct in zip(value_counts.index, value_counts, percentages)])
      add_summary(summary)

    else:
      # Numerical variables
      sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True, bins=bins, ax=ax)
      ax.set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')

      # Add summary statistics
      mean = df[col].mean()
      median = df[col].median()
      std = df[col].std()

      stats_text = f"Mean: {mean:.2f}\nMedian: {median:.2f}\nStd Dev: {std:.2f}"
      add_summary(stats_text)


  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

# Visualization functions
def set_plot_title(ax, col1, col2=None, plot_type=None, title=None):
    if title:
        ax.set_title(title)
    elif col2:
        ax.set_title(f'{plot_type} between {col1} and {col2}')
    else:
        ax.set_title(f'{plot_type} for {col1}')

def plot_barplot(col1, col2, ax, data, title=None):
    sns.countplot(x=col1, hue=col2, data=data, ax=ax)
    set_plot_title(ax, col1, col2, 'Bar Plot', title)

def plot_boxplot(col1, col2, ax, data, title=None):
    sns.boxplot(x=col1, y=col2, data=data, ax=ax)
    set_plot_title(ax, col1, col2, 'Box Plot', title)

def plot_scatterplot(col1, col2, hue, ax, data, title=None):
    scatter = ax.scatter(data[col1], data[col2],
                         c=data[hue].map({'Yes': 'blue', 'No': 'orange'}),
                         alpha=0.6)
    ax.set_xlabel(col1)
    ax.set_ylabel(col2)
    set_plot_title(ax, col1, col2, 'Scatter Plot', title)

    # Create a custom legend
    legend_elements = [
        plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', label='Resigned',
                   markerfacecolor='blue', markersize=10),
        plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', label='Not Resigned',
                   markerfacecolor='orange', markersize=10)
    ]
    ax.legend(handles=legend_elements, loc='upper left')

def plot_histogram(col, hue, ax, data, title=None):
    sns.histplot(data[data[hue] == 'Yes'][col], label='Resigned', kde=True, ax=ax)
    sns.histplot(data[data[hue] == 'No'][col], label='Not Resigned', kde=True, ax=ax)
    ax.legend()
    set_plot_title(ax, col, plot_type='Histogram', title=title)

# Visualization runner
def create_visualizations(pairs_barplot, pairs_boxplot, pairs_scatterplot, pairs_histogram, data):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(4, 3, figsize=(20, 24))

    # Plot bar plots
    for i, (col1, col2) in enumerate(pairs_barplot):
        row, col_idx = divmod(i, 3)
        plot_barplot(col1, col2, axs[row, col_idx], data)

    # Plot box plots
    for i, (col1, col2) in enumerate(pairs_boxplot):
        row, col_idx = divmod(i + len(pairs_barplot), 3)
        plot_boxplot(col1, col2, axs[row, col_idx], data)

    # Plot scatter plot
    for i, (col1, col2, hue) in enumerate(pairs_scatterplot):
        row, col_idx = divmod(i + len(pairs_barplot) + len(pairs_boxplot), 3)
        plot_scatterplot(col1, col2, hue, axs[row, col_idx], data)

    # Plot histogram
    for i, (col, hue) in enumerate(pairs_histogram):
        row, col_idx = divmod(i + len(pairs_barplot) + len(pairs_boxplot) + len(pairs_scatterplot), 3)
        plot_histogram(col, hue, axs[row, col_idx], data)


    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Define pairs of columns to analyze
pairs_barplot = [

    ('BusinessTravel', 'Resigned'),
    ('WorkLifeBalance', 'Resigned'),

3. Data Modeling¶

To create effective clustering models using k-means and DBSCAN for analyzing employee attrition, we should focus on variables that are most likely to influence an employee's decision to stay or leave. We will pre process the data by ensure all variables are properly scaled, and the categorical ones labeled.

KMeans is a method that groups data into a set number of clusters. It works by putting similar data points together based on how close they are to each other. We'll create a graph called the "elbow method" to help us figure out how many clusters we should use.

DBSCAN is another way to group data, but it looks for areas where there are lots of data points close together. It doesn't need you to decide how many groups to make beforehand. We'll use something called a "K-Distance Graph" to help set up DBSCAN correctly.

def plot_k_distance_graph(data, k):
    nearest_neighbors = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=k)
    neighbors = nearest_neighbors.fit(data)
    distances, indices = neighbors.kneighbors(data)
    distances = np.sort(distances[:, k-1])
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(distances)
    plt.title(f'K-Distance Graph for k={k}')
    plt.xlabel('Data Points sorted by distance')
    plt.ylabel(f'Distance to {k}-th Nearest Neighbor')
    plt.show()

def perform_clustering(data, variables, max_clusters=10):
    data_to_cluster = data[variables]

    # KMeans Elbow method
    wcss = []
    for i in range(1, max_clusters + 1):
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', max_iter=300, n_init=10, random_state=0)
        kmeans.fit(data_to_cluster)
        wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

    # Plot elbow curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(range(1, max_clusters + 1), wcss, marker='o')
    plt.title(f'Elbow Method ({", ".join(variables[:3])}...)')
    plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
    plt.ylabel('WCSS')
    plt.xticks(range(1, max_clusters + 1))
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    # Choose optimal number of clusters
    optimal_clusters = 4  # Modify this based on elbow curve observation

    # Perform KMeans clustering
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_clusters, init='k-means++', max_iter=300, n_init=10, random_state=0)
    kmeans_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(data_to_cluster)

    # DBSCAN
    # Plot k-distance graph to help choose eps
    plot_k_distance_graph(data_to_cluster, k=5)  
    
    
    # Perform DBSCAN clustering
    dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.6, min_samples=5)  # Modify this based on elbow curve observation
    dbscan_labels = dbscan.fit_predict(data_to_cluster)

    return kmeans_labels, dbscan_labels, optimal_clusters


# Perform clustering for all numerical variables

# Perform clustering for relevant variables
relevant_kmeans_labels, relevant_dbscan_labels, relevant_clusters = perform_clustering(data_scaled_all, relevant_variables)

def find_optimal_k(data, max_k):
    silhouette_scores = []
    k_values = range(2, max_k + 1)  # Start from 2 clusters

    for k in k_values:
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
        cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(data)
        silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(data, cluster_labels)
        silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_avg)
        print(f"For n_clusters = {k}, the average silhouette score is : {silhouette_avg:.4f}")

    # Plot silhouette scores
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(k_values, silhouette_scores, 'bo-')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
    plt.ylabel('Average Silhouette Score')
    plt.title('Silhouette Analysis for Optimal k')
    plt.show()

    # Find the best k
    optimal_k = k_values[np.argmax(silhouette_scores)]
    print(f"\nThe optimal number of clusters based on the silhouette method is: {optimal_k}")
    
    return optimal_k

# Usage example:
optimal_k = find_optimal_k(data_scaled_all[numerical_columns], max_k=10)
optimal_k_relevant = find_optimal_k(data_scaled_all[relevant_variables], max_k=10)

def analyze_clusters_comparison(data, cluster_labels, variables, method_name):
    def analyze_group(group_data, group_labels, group_name):
        group_data_with_clusters = group_data.copy()
        group_data_with_clusters['Cluster'] = group_labels
        
        cluster_summary = group_data_with_clusters.groupby('Cluster')[variables].mean()
        print(f"\nCluster Summaries ({method_name} - {group_name}):")
        print(cluster_summary)
        
        resignation_rate = group_data_with_clusters.groupby('Cluster')['Resigned'].mean()
        print(f"\nResignation Rates per Cluster ({method_name} - {group_name}):")
        print(resignation_rate)
        
        highest_resignation_cluster = resignation_rate.idxmax()
        highest_resignation_rate = resignation_rate.max()
        print(f'\nCluster with highest resignation rate: {highest_resignation_cluster}')
        print(f'Highest resignation rate: {highest_resignation_rate:.2%}')

    analyze_group(data, cluster_labels, "All Data")
    consultants_data = filter_consultants(data)
    consultants_mask = data['BusinessUnit'] == 'Consultants'
    consultants_labels = cluster_labels[consultants_mask]
    analyze_group(consultants_data, consultants_labels, "Consultants")

def analyze_gender_distribution_comparison(data, cluster_labels, method_name):
    def analyze_group(group_data, group_labels, group_name):
        group_data_with_clusters = group_data.copy()
        group_data_with_clusters['Cluster'] = group_labels
        
        gender_distribution = group_data_with_clusters.groupby('Cluster')['Gender'].value_counts(normalize=True).unstack()
        gender_distribution = gender_distribution.fillna(0)  # Replace NaN with 0
        
        print(f"\nGender Distribution per Cluster ({method_name} - {group_name}):")
        print(gender_distribution)
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        gender_distribution.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
        plt.title(f'Gender Distribution per Cluster ({method_name} - {group_name})')
        plt.xlabel('Cluster')
        plt.ylabel('Proportion')
        plt.legend(title='Gender')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    analyze_group(data, cluster_labels, "All Data")
    consultants_data = filter_consultants(data)
    consultants_mask = data['BusinessUnit'] == 'Consultants'
    consultants_labels = cluster_labels[consultants_mask]
    analyze_group(consultants_data, consultants_labels, "Consultants")

def evaluate_clustering(data, kmeans_labels, dbscan_labels, variables, title):
    # Calculate silhouette scores
    kmeans_silhouette = silhouette_score(data[variables], kmeans_labels)
    
    # For DBSCAN, we need to exclude noise points (labeled as -1)
    dbscan_points = data[variables][dbscan_labels != -1]
    dbscan_labels_filtered = dbscan_labels[dbscan_labels != -1]
    dbscan_silhouette = silhouette_score(dbscan_points, dbscan_labels_filtered) if len(np.unique(dbscan_labels_filtered)) > 1 else 0

    print(f"\nSilhouette Analysis for {title}")
    print(f"Silhouette Score for KMeans: {kmeans_silhouette:.4f}")
    print(f"Silhouette Score for DBSCAN: {dbscan_silhouette:.4f}")


# Evaluate clustering for all numerical variables
evaluate_clustering(data_scaled_all, all_num_kmeans_labels, all_num_dbscan_labels, numerical_columns, "All Numerical Variables")

# Evaluate clustering for relevant variables
evaluate_clustering(data_scaled_all, relevant_kmeans_labels, relevant_dbscan_labels, relevant_variables, "Relevant Variables")
